.SH "NAME"
File::Copy::Link \- extension for replacing a link by a copy of the linked file
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use File::Copy::Link;
\&  copylink \*(Aqfile.lnk\*(Aq; 
\&
\&  use File::Copy::Link qw(safecopylink);
\&  safecopylink \*(Aqfile.lnk\*(Aq;
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
.ie n .IP """copylink""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWcopylink\fR" 4
.IX Item "copylink"
reads the filename linked to by the argument and replaced 
the link with a copy of the file.  It opens a filehandle to read from
the link, deletes the link, and then copies the filehandle back to the
link.
.ie n .IP """safecopylink""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CWsafecopylink\fR" 4
.IX Item "safecopylink"
does the same as \f(CW\*(C`copylink\*(C'\fR but without the open-and-delete
manouvre.  Instead, it uses \f(CW\*(C`File::Spec::Link\*(C'\fR to find the target of the
link and copies from there.
.PP
This module is mostly a wrapper round \f(CW\*(C`File::Spec::Link::linked\*(C'\fR and 
\&\f(CW\*(C`File::Copy::copy\*(C'\fR, the functionality is available in a command line
script \fIcopylink\fR.
.SS "\s-1EXPORT\s0"
.IX Subsection "EXPORT"
Nothing by default, can export \f(CW\*(C`copylink\*(C'\fR, `\f(CW\*(C`safecopylink\*(C'\fR.
